  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Criminalize money laundering activities\n- Establish reporting requirements for cash transactions over $10,000\n- Impose penalties and fines for violations\n\n3. Specific Federal Laws:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Laundering of monetary instruments)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Engaging in monetary transactions in property derived from specified unlawful activity)\n\n4. State Laws:\n- Many states have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws\n- Typically mirror federal provisions with similar penalties and reporting requirements\n\n5. International Cooperation:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) guidelines\n- Mutual agreements with other countries to combat money laundering\n\nThese statutes provide a comprehensive legal framework for preventing, detecting, and prosecuting money laundering activities in the United States.",
